It s been a while since I posted  but I wanted to share this dish that I didn t get to try while in Korea  but did taste at  anjufrc while visiting my brother in D C  This particular version is my take on gungjung tteokbokki or royal court tteokbokki  a less spicy soy sauce based tteokbokki usually made with stir fried beef  Because hubby doesn t eat beef  I used thinly sliced pork shoulder butt instead which worked just as well in the recipe  And though I did say that this is a less spicy version  I couldn t resist adding some red and green Korean peppers as well as a  few  healthy shakes of black pepper  I also added some shimeji mushrooms  thinly sliced onions  and carrots  If you like tteok  rice cakes  this is a great recipe to try

Spicy ddukbokki that has been patented    Yoon Ok Yeon Grandmother s Ddukbokki was established in 1974 and has built a steady following for spicy rice cake lovers  They only have one level of spice  which is very spicy  and  it is the kind of spice that has a slow build up but definitely gets you sweating   Their ddukbokki and other items are super affordable  ranging from  1 4 per portion  and great for a quick bite  Since the ddukbokki itself is spicy and has a lot of spicy soup  it s best enjoyed with fried fish cake and dumpling    The fish cake is crispy and savory  and the dumpling is very simple  filled with little bits of clear noodles  This spicy meal was best enjoyed with Cool Piece  a refreshing and fruity drink that eases the tongue  My favorite flavor was peach   The restaurant had lots of indoor seating but was pretty crowded  Since service is super quick you can get in and out  or even get food for take out as well  I definitely recommend it for all the spicy lovers out there        떡볶이  윤옥연할매떡볶이  대구  맛집  eatlocal  supportlocal  koreanfood  ddukbokki  ricecake  spicy  dumpling  fishcake  daegu  korea  food  foodie  foodphotography  foodblogger  communityfoodwaves
